<br>
<br>
Than of course there are the chronological events that took place to lead to our present day &quot;Thanksgiving Day.&quot;  Settlers offering a turkey to Indians as a symbol of peace and thanks.  I'm not familiar with the exact history behind it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Personally, it should be a worldwide event because the concept behind it is admirable.  Anytime you rejoice over living and at the same are mindful and give thanks to those who allowed life to continue you're doing a great thing to them and yourself. <br>
